<p>
The regular icosahedron, often simply called "the" icosahedron, is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RegularPolyhedron.html">regular polyhe=
dron</a> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PlatonicSolid.html">P=
latonic
 solid</a> illustrated above having 12 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/PolyhedronVertex.html">polyhedron
 vertices</a>, 30 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PolyhedronEdge.h=
tml">polyhedron edges</a>, and 20 equivalent
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquilateralTriangle.html">equilat=
eral triangle</a> faces, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/e=
quations/RegularIcosahedron/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"m=
ax-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"43" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"20{3}">. It is illustrated above together with a wireframe version
 and a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Net.html">net</a> that can =
be used for its construction.
</p>
<p>
The regular icosahedron is also the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/UniformPolyhedron.html">uniform polyhedron</a> with Maeder index 22 (Maed=
er 1997), Wenninger index 4 (Wenninger 1989), Coxeter index
 25 (Coxeter <i>et al. </i>1954), and Har'El index 27 (Har'El 1993). It is =
described
 by the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SchlaefliSymbol.html">Schl=
=C3=A4fli symbol</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equat=
ions/RegularIcosahedron/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-h=
eight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"40" height=3D"21" alt=3D"{=
3,5}"> and <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WythoffSymbol.html">Wyt=
hoff symbol</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/=
RegularIcosahedron/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height=
:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39" height=3D"24" alt=3D"5|23">=
. Coxeter <i>et al. </i>(1999) have
 shown that there are 58 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Icosahedr=
onStellations.html">icosahedron stellations</a>
 (giving a total of 59 solids when the icosahedron itself is included).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"530.943" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/IcosahedronProjections_1000.svg" =
class=3D"" alt=3D"IcosahedronProjections">
</div>
<p>
A number of symmetric projections of the regular icosahedron are illustrate=
d above.
</p>
<p>
The regular icosahedron is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram=
.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wol=
fram.com/language/ref/Icosahedron.html">Icosahedron</a></tt>[]
 or <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/UniformPolyhed=
ron.html">UniformPolyhedron</a></tt>[<tt>"Icosahedron"</tt>],
 and precomputed properties are available as <tt><a href=3D"http://referenc=
e.wolfram.com/language/ref/PolyhedronData.html">PolyhedronData</a></tt>[<tt=
>"Icosahedron"</tt>].
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/gifs/icosah-o.jpg" class=
=3D"" style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"300" alt=3D"Origam=
i icosahedron">
</div>
<p>
Two icosahedra constructed in <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Orig=
ami.html">origami</a> are illustrated above (Gurkewitz and Arnstein 1995, p=
.&nbsp;53). This construction uses 30 triangle
 edge modules, each made from a single sheet of origami paper.
</p>
<p>
Two icosahedra appears as polyhedral "stars" in M.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Escher's 19=
48 wood engraving "Stars" (Forty 2003, Plate 43).
</p>
<p>
There are 43380 distinct nets for the icosahedron, the same number as for t=
he <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Dodecahedron.html">dodecahedron=
</a> (Bouzette and Vandamme, Hippenmeyer 1979,
 Buekenhout and Parker 1998).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"182.576" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/IcosahedralGraph_500.svg" class=
