</div>
<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DualPolyhedron.html">dual poly=
hedron</a> of an icosahedron with unit edge lengths is the <a href=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/Dodecahedron.html">dodecahedron</a> with edge leng=
ths
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/RegularIcosahed=
ron/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=3D"1/phi">,
 where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/RegularIc=
osahedron/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRatio.html">golden r=
atio</a>. As a result, the centers of
 the faces of an icosahedron form a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/Dodecahedron.html">dodecahedron</a>,
 and vice versa, illustrated above (Steinhaus 1999, pp.&nbsp;199-201).
</p>
<p>
In particular, fifteen <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRecta=
ngle.html">golden rectangles</a> span the interior of the icosahedron. Thes=
e rectangles have 30 edges, and each edge pairs
 up with its opposite edge to form a golden rectangle
</p>
<p>
There are 59 distinct icosahedra when each <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wol=
fram.com/Triangle.html">triangle</a> is colored differently (Coxeter 1969).=
 More general question of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Polyhedr=
onColoring.html">polyhedron
 coloring</a> can be addressed using the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfr=
am.com/PolyaEnumerationTheorem.html">P=C3=B3lya
 enumeration theorem</a>.
</p>
